Three layers to start with, and we can add complexity later:

Layer One — The Performed World What everyone lives in. Not fake exactly — just heavily curated. Society, routine, relationships, ambition. The "game" being played unconsciously. It mirrors our real world in all its brokenness — class, loneliness, digital numbness, performative connection. This is where your story starts.

Layer Two — The Bleed The space between frequencies. This is where the glitches happen. Where the open field exists. Where the sages sit. It's not another world — it's the gap between worlds made visible. Most people pass through it every day without noticing — in that moment between sleep and waking, in sudden inexplicable deja vu, in the feeling that a conversation already happened. The awakened can hold still in the Bleed instead of passing through it.

Layer Three — The Signal Nobody fully lives here. It's what's broadcasting the Performed World. The source. Even the fully awakened only catch fragments of it — like hearing a radio station through static. This is where your conspiracy lives. Someone or something is running the broadcast. And the closer your protagonists get to it, the more the Performed World tries to correct them — not violently, just quietly. Opportunities disappear. People forget conversations. Reality edits itself.

THE CHARACTERS — who they are at their core

Him — let's call him the Receiver He's not special by choice or destiny. He's special because he's porous — always has been. Feels too much, notices too much, shakes it off because what else do you do. His detachment isn't coldness — it's self-protection from a world that never quite felt calibrated to him. He's funny probably. Functional. Has people who love him. That's crucial — he has stakes in the Performed World, which makes every step away from it genuinely costly.

Her — the Tuner Alternate timeline version of him, yes — but she's been awake long enough that she's developed a completely different personality around the same core. Where he absorbs everything, she has learned to transmit — to move through the Performed World deliberately, leaving nothing for it to grab onto. She's not cold either. She's precise. And underneath the precision is the same longing he hasn't named yet — because she has named it, and it didn't help. She's looking for others like herself not out of hope exactly. More like — she's building something, and she needs people who can see what she sees.

The Sages Not teachers. Not guides. They're people who found the Bleed and stayed. They exist at threshold places — specific spots in the city, in nature, in half-abandoned spaces — where Layer One is thin. They're not wise in a comforting way. They're wise the way someone is wise after surviving something they can't fully describe. Each sage encountered is slightly different. Same function, different frequency. The idea that they might be test dummies planted by someone higher up — keep that. Don't reveal it early. Let it sit as unease.

