The horror of hyper scale isn't seeing how big it is. It's realizing you can't find the edges. Every time your characters think they've found the wall — there's more wall behind it.

That's what loses your mind from traditional storytelling. Traditional gives you a villain with a lair and a plan. This gives you a system with no center and individuals who service it without knowing its full shape. Even the antagonists don't know everything. They know their part. That's the insane part.

The antagonists — let's make them specific now

Give me this — what kind of person, in the real world, do you find most quietly terrifying? Not loud evil. The specific kind of person who makes you feel like something is wrong but you can't say what.

That feeling is your antagonist's texture.
